    <!-- ESSAY -->
    <article class="paper" aria-label="Essay">
      <p class="lede">
        I keep noticing something in myself: even when I don‚Äôt want to ‚Äúbelieve,‚Äù my mind still searches for a shape
        to hold onto. A story. A reason. A center of gravity. And I think that impulse is ancient.
      </p>

      <div class="body">
        <h2>Belief is older than knowledge</h2>
        <p>
          If you drop me into a world where lightning splits the sky, crops fail, a child gets sick, and the night is
          full of predators, I‚Äôm not going to calmly wait for a peer-reviewed explanation. I will reach for something
          that reduces fear and uncertainty <em>now</em>. I will attach meaning to patterns. I will invent causes when I
          don‚Äôt have answers.
        </p>
        <p>
          That‚Äôs not stupidity. It‚Äôs survival. Belief is a tool the brain uses to compress chaos into something you can
          carry. A way to coordinate with other people. A way to make pain feel less random. In that sense, belief isn‚Äôt
          the opposite of intelligence ‚Äî it‚Äôs a default human response to not knowing.
        </p>

        <figure class="inline-media" aria-label="Inline image">
          <img src={inlineImages[0].src} alt={inlineImages[0].alt} loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
          <figcaption>{inlineImages[0].cap}</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h2>From spirits to systems</h2>
        <p>
          When I look at history, it feels like a long migration of explanations. First, we had spirits: the river is
          angry, the forest is watching, the storm has a personality. Then gods: specialized, named, negotiated with,
          punished by, protected by. Then religions: organized belief ‚Äî with ethics, rituals, belonging, identity.
        </p>
        <p>
          And then something subtle happened: we started getting reliable answers from nature itself. Not from temples,
          not from kings, not from myths ‚Äî from experiments. From repeating the same test and getting the same result.
          From technology that works even if you don‚Äôt ‚Äúbelieve‚Äù in it.
        </p>

        <figure class="inline-media" aria-label="Inline image">
          <img src={inlineImages[1].src} alt={inlineImages[1].alt} loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
          <figcaption>{inlineImages[1].cap}</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <div class="callout" role="note" aria-label="Callout">
          <p class="callout-title">A thought I can‚Äôt unsee</p>
          <p class="callout-text">
            A belief can survive without proof. A technology can‚Äôt. If it doesn‚Äôt work, it dies.
            That pressure shapes cultures over time.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h2>Modern gods don‚Äôt look like gods</h2>
        <p>
          Here‚Äôs the part that feels uncomfortable: I don‚Äôt think we ‚Äústopped believing.‚Äù I think we just upgraded the
          costumes.
        </p>
        <p>
          Today, many of our gods are abstract:
          money, nation, ideology, status, the algorithm, productivity, ‚Äúthe market,‚Äù ‚Äúthe future,‚Äù ‚Äúsuccess.‚Äù
          None of these are physical objects you can touch ‚Äî yet people will sacrifice sleep, relationships, health,
          and sometimes morality for them.
        </p>
        <p>
          They function like gods because they:
          offer identity (‚Äúwho am I?‚Äù), promise safety (‚Äúwhat will protect me?‚Äù), define virtue (‚Äúwhat is good?‚Äù),
          and punish heresy (‚Äúwhat happens if I refuse?‚Äù).
        </p>

        <figure class="inline-media" aria-label="Inline image">
          <img src={inlineImages[2].src} alt={inlineImages[2].alt} loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
          <figcaption>{inlineImages[2].cap}</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h2>Why new gods are harder to create now</h2>
        <p>
          I have this theory ‚Äî not as a physicist, not as a historian, just as someone watching the world closely:
          in older eras, gaps in knowledge were huge, and belief could colonize those gaps easily.
          But now, many gaps are shrinking fast.
        </p>
        <p>
          When we can explain eclipses, disease, the motion of planets, the age of the Earth, the chemistry of life ‚Äî
          a lot of the ‚Äúmystery space‚Äù that used to be filled with confident gods becomes‚Ä¶ smaller.
          Not because the universe is less mysterious, but because our explanations are more precise.
        </p>
        <p>
          That precision changes culture. It doesn‚Äôt erase belief, but it makes it harder for a brand-new god to
          become universally convincing. The world is too connected, too cross-checked, too recorded.
          A new belief system gets stress-tested immediately.
        </p>

        <h2>But meaning still has to live somewhere</h2>
        <p>
          Even if science answers ‚Äúhow,‚Äù it doesn‚Äôt automatically answer ‚Äúwhy should I care?‚Äù.
          And that‚Äôs where belief sneaks back in ‚Äî through values. Through what we choose to protect.
          Through what we treat as sacred.
        </p>
        <p>
          Sometimes I wonder if the next ‚Äúgods‚Äù won‚Äôt be supernatural at all ‚Äî but ethical frameworks we treat as
          untouchable: dignity, consciousness, truth, responsibility. Or maybe the sacred will become smaller and more
          personal: your family, your craft, your integrity. A private religion of attention.
        </p>

        <hr class="rule" />

        <h2>Where I land today</h2>
        <p>
          I don‚Äôt want to pretend I‚Äôm above belief. I have my own versions too. I just try to notice them.
          I try to keep the door open: ‚ÄúWhat if I‚Äôm wrong?‚Äù.
        </p>
        <p>
          If there‚Äôs one thing I want to practice, it‚Äôs this: replacing blind belief with
          <strong>curious belief</strong> ‚Äî beliefs that are allowed to evolve when reality disagrees.
          Not faith as a wall, but faith as a temporary bridge.
        </p>

        <p class="sig">‚Äî Ugurcan</p>
      </div>
    </article>

